e City: A Legacy of Organism-Environment Interaction at Every Scale -- t17. Natural Cities, Unnatural Energy? -- t18. Children and Nature in the City -- tConclusion -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUrban and natural environments are often viewed as entirely separate entities - human settlements as the domain of architects and planners, and natural areas as untouched wilderness. This dichotomy continues to drive decision-making in subtle ways, but with the mounting pressures of global climate change and declining biodiversity, it is no longer viable. New technologies are promising to provide renewable energy sources and greener designs, but real change will require a deeper shift in values, attitudes, and perceptions. A timely and important collection, The Natural City explores how to integrate the natural environment into healthy urban centres from philosophical, religious, socio-political, and planning perspectives. Recognizing the need to better link the humanities with public policy, The Natural City offers unique insights for the development of an alternative vision of urban life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSustainable urban development. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology). 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aCameron, W.S.K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobb, John B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoltz, Bruce V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazebrook, Trish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id